ce:section.ce:para:
To make clear the role of the function groups in the catalytic POD-like process, function groups deactivation agents such as PH reacting specially with the ketonic carbonyl (CO) as CDs-PH, BA with hydroxy (C-OH) as CDs-BA and BrPE with carboxyl groups (OC-O) as CDs-BrPE on the CDs were used to verify the catalytical sites of the CDs [37]. These reactions were confirmed by the change of zeta potential, FITR and XPS spectra of CDs (
                           Fig. S4
                         − 6). It can be seen that zeta potentials of CDs reacting with function groups deactivation agents were different with that of parent CDs (
                           Fig. S4

                        ). Meanwhile, in their FIIR, the appearing vibration band at 1840 cm-1of CDs-PH, which can be ascribed to the formation of CN bonds after titration of pH with CDs, and an weak increase at 1730 cm−1 peak corresponding to the ester group for formation of CDs-BA (
                           Fig. S5

                        ) 
                        [37]. Furthermore, from the O 1 s XPS spectra, the intensity of the group corresponding to their deactivating reaction decreased accordingly (
                           Fig. S6

                        ). All these results confirmed the specific reaction of function groups such as CO, C-OH and OC-O of CDs with their deactivation agents which can be selected to investigate the active catalytic site for their good POD-like activity [37,39,45]. The catalytical contributions of CO, C-OH and OC-O of CDs were evaluated by comparing their enzymatic activity with parent CDs. It has been found that the CDs-BA which can increace CO in the titration process showed much higher enzymatic activity, whereas CDs-PH which reduced the CO showed much lower enzymatic activity (
                           Fig. S7
                        ) and the catalytic activity of the CDs-BrPE showed comparable enzymatic activity as that of the parent CDs. Furthermore, it was worthy mention that the catalytically active sites of CO groups were almost the same after the catalytic reaction confirmed by the XPS analysis of CDs (
                           Fig. S8
                        ). These results confirmed that the CO groups were the most active sites involved in the catalytic reaction [37].

The successful verification of CDs that had the ability to act as POD, CAT, SOD and •OH scavengers prompted us to further explore its practical application in ROS scavenging in vitro. The biocompatibility of the CDs was investigated by CCK-8 cell viability assay. The survival rate of RAW264.7 cells remained above 80% even when the 

                        CDs were cultured at relatively high concentration (20 μg/mL), which revealed that the CDs showed good biocompatibility (
                           Fig. S14
                        ). To understand the intracellular transport mechanism of CDs, the endocytosis pathway of the CDs was explored, and it found that the uptake of CDs was an energy-dependent process mainly mediated by clathrin-mediated endocytosis pathways (
                           Fig. S15, S16
                        ) [50,51].

In addition, we used CDs and Lyso-Tracker Red for co-localization, and found that CDs entered the cell and targeted the Lysosome (pH 4.5–5.5), because alkaline ligands were most likely to be enriched in the acidic organelles (
                           Fig. S17
                        ) [52]. Cell-permeable fluorescent probe, 2′,7′-dichlorodihydrofluorescein diacetate (DCFH-DA), which can enter into the cells and oxidized to green-fluorescent 2′,7′-dichlorofluorescein (DCF) by ROS, was used to assess the ROS scavenging ability of the CDs [53]. The fluorescence intensity of DCF was directly proportional to the level of intracellular ROS (
                           Fig. S18
                        ). As show in Fig. 3
                        A, the intracellular fluorescence intensities were greatly decreased with the increasing concentration of pre-incubated CDs, confirming that the CDs were really to deplete the intracellular ROS efficiently (
                           Fig. S19
                        ). Besides, cell imaging was performed with the same concentration of CDs alone, and we found that the fluorescence of low-concentration CDs was very weak under experimental conditions, which hardly interfered with the detection of ROS in living cells (
                           Fig. S1

                        A, S20).
